{{More citations needed|date=June 2007}} [[File:Harrison Allen.jpg|thumb|]] '''Harrison Allen''' (1841–1897) was an [[United States|American]] physician and [[anatomist]], born in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|Philadelphia]]. He graduated from the [[Perelman School of Medicine|medical department of the University of Pennsylvania]] in 1861,<ref name="AMB">{{Cite AMB1920|wstitle=Allen, Harrison}}</ref> and in 1862 became a [[surgeon]] in the [[United States Army]] and served until the conclusion of the [[American Civil War|Civil War]] in 1865. Doctor Allen should not be confused with the Union Army officer who was colonel of the 151st Pennsylvania Volunteer Infantry Regiment, who was mustered out July 31, 1863 and later was awarded the grade of brevet brigadier general.<ref>Eicher, John H., and [[David J. Eicher]], ''Civil War High Commands.'' Stanford: Stanford University Press, 2001. {{ISBN|0-8047-3641-3}}. p. 101</ref><ref>Boatner, Mark Mayo, III. ''The Civil War Dictionary.'' New York: McKay, 1988. {{ISBN|0-8129-1726-X}}. First published 1959 by McKay. p. 9</ref>
In 1865 he was made professor of comparative anatomy and medical zoölogy at the [[University of Pennsylvania]]. He was transferred in 1878 to the chair of [[physiology]], which he occupied until 1895.
==Publications== In addition to many papers contributed to medical journals, he authored a number of books: * ''Outlines of Comparative Anatomy and Medical Zoölogy'' (1867) * ''Studies in the Facial Region'' (1874) * An Analysis of the Life Form in Art'' (1875) * ''System of Human Anatomy'' (1880)
