'''Menhuan''' ({{zh|s=门宦|t=門宦|p=Ménhuàn}}) is a term used by [[Hui people|Chinese-speaking Muslims]] for a Chinese-style [[Sufi order]]. The leaders of a menhuan over the ages form a chain of spiritual succession, known in Arabic as ''[[silsilah]]'', which goes back to the order's founder in China (e.g., [[Ma Laichi]] or [[Ma Mingxin]]), and beyond, toward his teachers in Arabia.<ref name=dillon113>{{cite book |publisher=Routledge |year=1999 |isbn=0-7007-1026-4 |title=China's Muslim Hui community: migration, settlement and sects |author= Michael Dillon |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=hUEswLE4SWUC |pages=113–114 }} One of Dillon's main sources is: {{cite book | title =中国伊斯兰教派与门宦制度史略 (Zhongguo Yisilan jiaopai yu menhuan zhidu shilue) (A sketch of the history of Chinese Islamic sects and the ''menhuan'' system) |author= 馬通 ( Ma Tong) |place=Yinchuan |publisher= 宁夏人民出版社 (Ningxia Renmin Chubanshe) |year=1983 }} </ref>
==Origin of the term== The term ''menhuan'' itself is of comparatively recent origin: according to [[Ma Tong]] (1983), it was first attested in an essay by the [[Linxia Hui Autonomous Prefecture|Hezhou Prefecture]] Magistrate [[Yang Zengxin]] dated 1897.<ref name=dillon113/> It has been suggested by Chinese researchers that it has developed from ''menfa'' ({{lang|zh-Hans|门阀}}), meaning "powerful and influential family", or ''menhu'' ({{lang|zh-Hans|门户}}), which has been used in the [[Northwestern China]] to mean "gateway" or "faction".<ref name=dillon113/> <!-- ==History== Chinese authors often talk about the "Four Great ''menhuan''s", the list usually including [[Jahriyya]] (哲合忍耶), [[Khufiyya]] (虎夫耶)), [[Qadiryya]] (尕德忍耶 or 戛迪林耶 or 嘎吉忍耶), and (库布忍耶). 尕 = [gǎ] --> ==References== {{Reflist}}
